"Yes, chief. They must be on their way now, we've given them enough time to get rations from the mess." At 5:00 sharp, Company Exodus was assembled at the vehicle park. Shaw climbed onto a crate and began to speak.
"We're deploying to FOB I-131, 80 kilometers from Ianlos. We need to support the ongoing siege and the planned attack on Ianlos to quell the insurgency. From there, we'll have an advanced position and a base at the foot of the mountains," Shaw explained. "Gather your units, and board."
The company dispersed, each one joining their unit, and the sergeants made them board the tanks. Cohren climbed aboard one of the armoured vehicles, at the front of the convoy, and joined Nemic, Craith, and two new recruits. Cohren remembered their arrival a few days earlier, but he didn't know much about them. Sitting on the side, his legs dangling, he adjusted his backpack and his radio equipment, which was connected to his earpiece and throat mic.
"Hey Cohren, has Harris got Snowball yet?" asked Nemic as they settled in.
"Are you talking about the chicken he stole?" Cohren remembered the morning they had stolen it from a farm. "Yes, I'm sure".
Cohren glanced at one of the tanks and spotted Harris with his unit. From the back of his backpack, he could just make out the movement of a small chicken bobbing its head to observe its surroundings.
"Ouais, he's got it", replied Cohren as the tank turret swung open with a clatter to let his commander pass.
"All the tanks were on the move," declared calmly, but clearly the commander in his helmet.
"About an hour in, one of the new recruits, named Orson in Cohren's memory, spoke up. 'Lieutenant, you've been here since the start of the war, haven't you?'"
"Ah, Operation Thunderstorm", replied Cohren. "We thought we'd wrap it up in a few weeks, but... we underestimated them."
"Underestimating them is a mild word," Nemic said, joining the conversation. "They had more guns and men than we anticipated. They managed to take down the UFS Revenant in the first two weeks, and Erebus last month. Bloody hell, we should be seeing them from the road where we are."
"Well, I'll hold up for the Federation," Orson said with a hint of provocation. "I won't let these terrorists scare me off."
"You say that now, but from experience, I know that 18-year-old new recruits like you take cover as soon as they hear a shot," declared Craith.
"I think we'll get settled in quickly," said Cohren with a laugh. Orson didn't pursue the conversation.
"Exodus XO, Exodus CO," crackled Cohren's radio. "We're detecting thermal signatures about 300 meters out, 20 degrees right."
Cohren climbed atop the tank and slipped on his optical glasses. Activating thermal vision, he could see thermal signatures in the distance.
"Ah, I see them," replied Cohren over his throat mic.
"What enemies?" asked the other recruit, Natayla.
"It's hard to tell," declared Cohren. He activated his mic and said: "Company Exodus, don't fire unless they fire at us, let them out."
As they drew closer, the small thermal signatures went from fuzzy patches to more defined shapes. As they got even closer, one of them ran towards something, grabbed it, and then sprinted back to the small ridge where they were. The silhouettes took up firing positions.
"We have contacts," Shaw shouted over the radio, as orange tracers were fired from the ridge.
"Tank 1-2 and 1-3, 25 degrees right, 275 meters. 'Fire'," the tank platoon commander shouted over the radio. Tank 1-2 and 1-3 opened fire, their shells flew towards the ridge and exploded, launching mud and rocks into the air.
"Deploy the Sentis," Knoxx shouted, observing the ridge through his binoculars. The rear of one of the Cerberus opened and a disarmed soldier wearing a special helmet stepped out. He bellowed orders into a square microphone and two Sentis, or Sentinelles as they were officially known, sprinted out. Their thin metal arms and legs swung forward as they launched into a sprint. They were armed, but their arms were slung over their backs.
"Are we going to kill them or capture them?" asked Craith as they watched them.
"It seems we'll capture them," Cohren said as the two Sentinelles disappeared in a cloud of smoke and ash. Gunfire and cries echoed from the ridge, but quickly died down. A moment later, the two Sentinelles returned, dragging someone behind them, whose boots were trailing on the ground. Once safely back with the platoon, they threw the individual to the ground. He groaned in pain as he fell into the mud and snow.
"How many?"
"Three dead, chief," the Sentinel replied. "The others fled on foot."
Shaw nodded and turned to Cohren and Craith, who stood beside him. "Both of you, would you be so kind as to get rid of this man?"
